>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=G9806167"><gtr:id>8FA9FD35-5AAF-48AC-973E-F954E56B4E37</gtr:id><gtr:title>Genomic Instability: Interplay between DNA replication, recombination and repair</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G9806167</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>We publish the results of our studies in high quality, peer-reviewed scientific journals. The principal investigator is also regularly invited to speak at major international conferences, to write reviews and to give seminars at universities and research units. Members of the group have also given presentations on aspects of DNA damage and cancer at 6th form Summer Schools and Open Days, and to school 6th form biology classes. Personal web pages provide general information about our research.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>We study the molecular biology of recombination, how recombination pathways provide ways to protect the integrity of the genome, and how recombination proteins integrate with DNA replication, transcription and repair systems to promote efficient chromosome duplication and accurate transmission of the genome. The programme of work is framed around a numbert of interlinked projects focussed on the RecG, RuvABC, RusA, RdgC and RecN proteins of Escherichia coli, and on the RadB and Hjc proteins of Haloferax volcanii. We will apply molecular, biochemical and structural methods to study these proteins, and combine these with genetics and cell biology to investigate their function. We will also study DNA double-strand break repair systems, especially the non-homologous end-joining pathway we have recently found to operate in E. coli, and exploit the H. volcanii model we have established to investigate recombination and DNA repair in the archaeal domain of life using genetic and molecular methods of analysis.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>1998-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>3418623</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>University of Aberdeen</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:department>College of Life Sciences and Medicine</gtr:department><gtr:description>Genomic Instability: Conflicts between DNA replication and transcription</gtr:description><gtr:id>8C6910B0-063B-44E7-98E9-E7CA0CD85218</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Guy CP, et al. (2009) Rep provides a second motor at the replisome to promote duplication of protein-bound DNA. Mol Cell 36:654-666.
